Using LSI loading matrices as the whiten matrices to infer shared independent components

Weixu Wang

2022/3/9

In this tutorial, I will demonstrate ICAnet V2s ability to integrate scRNA-seq dataset from different sequencing platforms. Following the tutorial give by https://htmlpreview.github.io/?https://github.com/WWXkenmo/ICAnet/blob/master/vignettes/Pancreas_Tutorial2.html. We first load and process our datasets, all datasets could be downloaded from https://hemberg-lab.github.io/scRNA.seq.datasets/human/pancreas/

1. Preprocessing

suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(Seurat))
suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(ICAnet))
suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(SingleCellExperiment))
suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(cowplot))

baron <- readRDS("/mnt/data1/weixu/HiDe/pancreas/baron-human.rds")
muraro <- readRDS("/mnt/data1/weixu/HiDe/pancreas/muraro.rds")
segerstolpe <- readRDS("/mnt/data1/weixu/HiDe/pancreas/segerstolpe.rds")
xin <- readRDS("/mnt/data1/weixu/HiDe/pancreas/xin.rds")
baron_exp <- counts(baron)
segerstolpe_exp <- counts(segerstolpe)
muraro_exp <- normcounts(muraro)
xin_exp <- normcounts(xin)
geneID <- rownames(muraro_exp)
geneID_str <- strsplit(geneID,split="_")
for(i in 1:length(geneID)){
  geneID[i] <- geneID_str[[i]][1]
}
rownames(muraro_exp) <- geneID
geneID <- c(rownames(baron_exp),rownames(muraro_exp),rownames(segerstolpe_exp),rownames(xin_exp))
geneID <- names(table(geneID))[table(geneID)==4]
baron_exp <- baron_exp[geneID,]
segerstolpe_exp <- segerstolpe_exp[geneID,]
muraro_exp <- muraro_exp[geneID,]
xin_exp <- xin_exp[geneID,]


batch <- c(baron$human, rep("segerstolpe",(ncol(segerstolpe_exp))),rep("muraro",ncol(muraro_exp)),rep("xin",ncol(xin_exp)))
celltype <- c(as.character(as.matrix(baron$cell_type1)),
              as.character(as.matrix(segerstolpe$cell_type1)),
              as.character(as.matrix(muraro$cell_type1)),as.character(as.matrix(xin$cell_type1)))
pancreas <- CreateSeuratObject(cbind(baron_exp,segerstolpe_exp,muraro_exp,xin_exp))
pancreas$batch <- batch
pancreas$celltype <- celltype

### select part of cells to conduct analysis
pancreas <- pancreas[,pancreas$celltype %in% c("acinar","alpha","beta","delta","ductal","endothelial","epsilon","gamma","macrophage","mast","schwann","stellate")]

pancreas.list <- SplitObject(pancreas, split.by="batch")
for(i in 1:length(pancreas.list)) {
   pancreas.list[[i]] <- NormalizeData(pancreas.list[[i]],verbose=FALSE)
   pancreas.list[[i]] <- ScaleData(pancreas.list[[i]],verbose=FALSE,scale.max=Inf)
   pancreas.list[[i]] <- FindVariableFeatures(pancreas.list[[i]],selection.method="vst",nfeature=4000,verbose=FALSE)
}
pancreas.feature <- SelectIntegrationFeatures(object.list = pancreas.list,nfeatures = 4000)

Now we have data list contains scaled Seurat objects from different batches, and the features for integration

2. Using Latent semantic indexing corrected loading matrices as whiten matrices to identify independent shared components

Using could use following simple code to identify independent shared components

list <- SharedBasalComponents(pancreas.list,pancreas.feature,reduct.dim = 30,W.top=2.5)

which would identify 36 basal components from list objects

3. Run ICAnet

Now, run ICAnet to perform batch effects corrections and clustering!

## the getPPI_String function could be downloaded from https://github.com/WWXkenmo/ICAnet/blob/master/getPPI_String.R
pancreas_merged <- list$mergedObject
hs_network_matrix <- getPPI_String(pancreas_merged,species = 9606)
pancreas_merged <- RunICAnet(pancreas_merged,list$basalcomp, PPI.net = hs_network_matrix, W.top=2,aucMaxRank = 300,ModuleSignificance=FALSE,cores=10,scale=FALSE)

pancreas_merged <- RunPCA(pancreas_merged,verbose=FALSE,features = rownames(pancreas_merged))
pancreas_merged <- RunUMAP(pancreas_merged, reduction = "pca", dims = 1:30, reduction.name = "umap",  reduction.key = "umap_")

alternatively, ICAnet V2 also return the LSI correct cell embedding vector into the seurat objects, and this embedding also could correct the batch effects
